# Use Enums for Multiple Constants

When you have several related constants (stages, modes, types, statuses), use an enum instead of separate constants or magic numbers/strings.

## Why

- Single source of truth and type safety
- Easier to extend and refactor
- Clear exhaustiveness in switches
- No scattered literals

## Do

```java
// ✅ GOOD: enum for stage types
public enum StageType {
    GRACE_PERIOD, STAGE_0, STAGE_1, STAGE_2, STAGE_3, STAGE_4
}

// ✅ GOOD: enum for modes or statuses
public enum RadiationLevel { NONE, LOW, MEDIUM, HIGH }
```

## Don't

```java
// ❌ BAD: separate int constants
public static final int STAGE_0 = 0;
public static final int STAGE_1 = 1;
public static final int STAGE_2 = 2;

// ❌ BAD: string literals as "constants"
if (status.equals("active")) { ... }

// ❌ BAD: magic numbers
if (level == 3) { ... }
```

## When to use enums

- Two or more related named values (e.g. statuses, modes, types)
- Values used in conditionals, method parameters, or return types
- When you might add more values later

Single, unrelated constants (e.g. `MAX_RETRIES = 3`) can stay as `static final` fields.
